    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1103284487" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1103284487" />
    <a title="Elagabalus" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/23937964-elagabalus"><img alt="Elagabalus" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1635584401p2/23937964.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1103284487?book_show_action=true">Nov 10, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Elagabalus" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Elagabalus" href="/user/show/23937964-elagabalus">Elagabalus</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/23937964-elagabalus?shelf=2014">2014</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/23937964-elagabalus?shelf=fantasy-scifi">fantasy-scifi</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/23937964-elagabalus?shelf=kid-lit">kid-lit</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1103284487" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12180447242678353756">I originally read the tripods series many years ago, during my adolescent on-again off-again love of books. This was during an on-again, when I fantastically wondered at the possibilities of a scifi story starring folks around my age. It was wonderful, but I&apos;m reading the series again to see how I feel about it now, and remind myself more of the story. I&apos;m starting with the prequel this time, whereas I originally started with the &apos;first&apos; one in the trilogy. I recall originally being disappointed</span>
  <span id="freeText12180447242678353756" style="display:none">I originally read the tripods series many years ago, during my adolescent on-again off-again love of books. This was during an on-again, when I fantastically wondered at the possibilities of a scifi story starring folks around my age. It was wonderful, but I'm reading the series again to see how I feel about it now, and remind myself more of the story. I'm starting with the prequel this time, whereas I originally started with the 'first' one in the trilogy. I recall originally being disappointed simply because I already knew what was going to happen (due to the continuing existence of tripods), but this time I found it highly enjoyable - adventurous, suspenseful, and meaningful.<br /><br />The first thing I noticed was how swiftly and excitedly written it is. It's also an interesting topic, a new theme of invasion different from what I expected. The concept of invading the minds rather than (or before the) primary physical invasion was very intriguing to me, particularly as one who has effectively unplugged my mind from most mass media, particularly commercialized television. I imagine my original reading had me thinking of television a different way, indeed.<br /><br />While I do like the perhaps-prophetic criticisms of television and mass media, I'm a bit confused by the story element that the characters fear that the plans of the tripods is to make everyone live in villages rather than cities. While I understand the matter of deindustrializing an enemy world, that doesn't appear a rational focus (the author thinks science = independent thought, when its foundation of mathematics commands subservient thought) - it's made out to be that localized communities are bad, metropolis is good.<br /><br />A major theme seems to be nationalism, and I like that the sense of nationalism creeps among the mind controlled and 'non'-mind-controlled. It's as though their minds were already prepared, active brainwashing or no. But, considering the era, I have a feeling that the cultural background here is a citizen of an empire criticising the post-wwii nationalist-anti-imperialist movements which actively limited the effects of those empires. The concept that 'we don't all need our own nations' (as one aryan I knew criticised of the scots), comes out of the brainwashed hypocrisy that the europeans can destroy and enslave entire peoples to build their american 'nation', but that marginalized peoples can't fight back. It's bullshit, and I have a sense john christopher is perpetuating this, despite never mentioning non-europeans. Hail the Europeans! as his characters might say.<br /><br />Moving on, I like that this book seems one of those prequels which is well-placed and important, rather than unnecessary. The writing style, beside well-paced, was written well in the first-person. The narration sounds like a journal, and while past-tense lessens intensity and suspense, it also draws me into the events and wondering what will happen next. It's a good achievement that it's a prequel, and while I know the tripods win, I'm interested in the story nonetheless.<br /><br />Finally, I don't like the descriptions of death, few as they are. Just needlessly graphic, as most books are. As for the suspense, I don't know how to describe my feeling about it properly, but I have a sense of appreciation yet fear of the suspenseful way fewer and fewer people are not brainwashed. I've had nightmares (and daymares) about such possibilities, and while it makes for good allegory and suspense, I still have some sense of wanting it to stop, which may tarnish an otherwise enjoyable fiction. This was particularly bad when I was a kid watching each version of the invasion of the body snatchers.<br /><br />Well, I'm excited for more!</span>
  <a data-text-id="12180447242678353756" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

