<div id="review_166982150" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/166982150" />
    <a title="Jamie Dacyczyn" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5407713-jamie-dacyczyn"><img alt="Jamie Dacyczyn" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1306204362p2/5407713.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/166982150?book_show_action=true">May 09, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jamie Dacyczyn" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jamie Dacyczyn" href="/user/show/5407713-jamie-dacyczyn">Jamie Dacyczyn</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5407713-jamie-dacyczyn?shelf=owned-books">owned-books</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5407713-jamie-dacyczyn?shelf=post-apoc-dystopian">post-apoc-dystopian</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5407713-jamie-dacyczyn?shelf=sci-fi">sci-fi</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer166982150" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16814882784807705713">It&apos;s been a while since I&apos;ve reread this Tripods prequel (I don&apos;t think I included it on my last reread of the trilogy), so I didn&apos;t actually remember a lot of the plot aside from some key points.<br/><br/>Overall, a little too short and prequel-ish to feel like there&apos;s a lot of character development or complex plotting. You ultimately KNOW where things are going to end up; this is just there to answer the how and why. <br/><br/>I feel like John Christopher must have heard some (totally justified) criticism for his</span>
  <span id="freeText16814882784807705713" style="display:none">It's been a while since I've reread this Tripods prequel (I don't think I included it on my last reread of the trilogy), so I didn't actually remember a lot of the plot aside from some key points.<br /><br />Overall, a little too short and prequel-ish to feel like there's a lot of character development or complex plotting. You ultimately KNOW where things are going to end up; this is just there to answer the how and why. <br /><br />I feel like John Christopher must have heard some (totally justified) criticism for his near total lack of female characters in the trilogy, because this prequel has to have at least five times as many named girls/women as in the entire trilogy. He doesn't go so far as to make the main character a girl, but at least the main character has a sister, so I guess that's something. <br /><br />At the end of the day, I don't think this prequel adds a whole lot to the series as a whole, but for readers who enjoy the trilogy and want to know How It All Began...there's this. It's FINE, but it's not amazing. I think I'd rate it one slot up from The Pool of Fire (final book in the trilogy) .</span>
  <a data-text-id="16814882784807705713" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


